&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from
[normal] Andrew Bodman (HSR 002)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1. The latest version of the HS2 Economic Case published at the end of October 2013 still contains faults 
[normal]some of 
[normal]which have been pointed out in earlier versions. 
[normal]Some other shortcomings are detailed too.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. My recommendation is to cancel HS2 now. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Overstated Benefits[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3. 
[normal]The economic case still uses
[normal] the basis that people do not work on trains and therefore any journey time saving results in added work (productivity). While
[normal] the value of time has been changed, the principle that a shorter journey time leads to more worker output has not changed. 
[normal]It is well known that many people work on trains whether using a laptop, iPad, smartphone or simply reading documents. To continue t
[normal]o ignore what happens in the real world is absurd.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4. 
[normal]Previously the Department for Transport had anticipated that about 30% of HS2 passengers would be on business. National Passenger Surveys have regularly reported a similar proportion of business travellers on intercity routes on the West Coast Mainline (WC
[normal]ML), Midland Mainline (MML) and East Coast Mainline (ECML). 
[normal]http://www.passengerfocus.org.uk/research/national-passenger-survey-introduction
[normal]    See Stakeholde
[normal]r Report
[normal]5. 
[normal]The latest HS2 economic case now anticipates a much higher proportion of business travellers than previously, e.g. 66% for London Manchester. Such a high proportion of business travellers 
[normal]is no longer in line with National Passenger Surveys.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6. 
[normal]The HS2 economic case for HS2 is still calculated on the basis that passenger 
[normal]ticket prices will carry no premium over those for classic rail journeys. This lack of premium ticket pricing in the DfT’s HS2 passenger demand modelling was strongly challeng
[normal]ed by the Public Accounts Committee in 2012. 
[normal]http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmpubacc/464/12041801.htm
[normal]   See questions 42 to 50
[normal] and their answers.
[normal]7. 
[normal]Currently there is a 20% ticket price premium for Ashford to London travellers on HS1 compared to a classic rail journey. In Europe, the ticket price premium is typically 70%. Recently the Secretary of State for Transport was quoted 
[normal]as saying 
[normal]in the context of HS2, 
[normal]“
[normal]If you turn up at the last minute, you are going to be paying a lot of money.”
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/10302224/HS2-Passengers-will-have-to-pay-a-lot-of-money-unless-they-book-ahead.html
[normal]8. If you take a 20% premium over Virgin trains for a return Birmingham London journey at
[normal] peak times, you 
[normal]would 
[normal]theoretically 
[normal]have the following alternatives
[normal] at 2013 prices:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chiltern Railways
[normal]              
[normal]  £95
[normal]Virgin Trains
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]£158
[normal]HS2
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]£189
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9. Ticket pricing does have an effect on demand, and to construct a HS2 passenger forecast without a price premium l
[normal]eads to overs
[normal]tated level of passenger demand.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10. 
[normal]All of the factors listed above result in a grossly overstated amount of 
[normal]benefits. Independent bodies
[normal] suggest a realistic be
[normal]nefit cost ratio for HS2 is 0.5, i.e. 50p back for every £1 spent.
[normal] 
[normal]That would be 
[normal]unsatisfactory by Treasury rules as well as being an irresponsible use of taxpayers’ money.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Designed in Bottleneck[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]11. 
[normal]Many of the main 
[normal]rail 
[normal]lines serving London are close to the maximum number of train paths that they can accommodate at peak times. 
[normal]Ultr
[normal]a high speed trains require g
[normal]reater stopping distances than
[normal] classic trains as a result of their greater kinetic energy. So an ultra high speed line can accommodate fewer trains per hour than a classic line. The UIC (International Union of Railways) has indicated that it is not safe to run more than 16 trains per h
[normal]our at 350 kph. 
[normal]See Figure 2
[normal]http://www.greengauge21.net/wp-content/uploads/Final-Report-Appendices-B-J.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12. The indicative schedule for HS2 phase two shows
[normal] 16 trains per hour planned for the Birmingham Interchange to 
[normal]the junction for the 
[normal]Heathrow spur section of the route. See figure 6-2 in PFMv4.3 Assumptions Report. 
[normal]http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%2020_PFM%20assumptions%20report.pdf
[normal]13. 
[normal]In addition
[normal] there are tentatively two trains
[normal] 
[normal]per hour to serve Heathrow. Lastly there are two more trains per hour to link with HS1 and 
[normal]presumably these go further north than Heathrow; this is in addition to the Old Oak Common service to HS1 service. So this shows that up to t
[normal]wenty trains per hour are intended on a 
[normal]section of 
[normal]line that can
[normal] safely handle 
[normal]only 
[normal]16 trains per hour. In other wo
[normal]rds there is an intention to spend £50 billion on a line that has no room for expansion s
[normal]e
[normal]ven years after it is built. 
[normal]The Victorians had considerably more foresight.
[normal] Contractor Atkins was aware of this issue in 2008 and documented it in their report “Beca
[normal]use Transport Matters”.
[normal]http://stophs2.org/news/7424-is-dft-misleading-us-part-2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Existing Commuter Overcrowding[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]14. However HS2 does not address the most pressing problems that the 
[normal]rail network currently experiences, which is that of overcrowded commuter trains. Over 120,000 rail passengers stand on trains during the morning peak three hours every weekday; DfT data for typical autumn day 2012.
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rail-passenger-numbers-and-crowding-on-weekdays-in-major-cities-in-england-and-wales-2012
[normal]15. The worst 
[normal]affected lines 
[normal]in terms of trains carrying standing passengers 
[normal]are those serving the following stations:
[normal]London Bridge
[normal]              
[normal]31,247
[normal]Waterloo
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]28,168
[normal]Victoria
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]14,337
[normal]Liverpool Street
[normal]              
[normal]12,205
[normal]Fenchurch Street
[normal]              
[normal]  8,143
[normal]e
[normal]tc.
[normal] 
[normal]16. A Transport for London study in 2007 
[normal]found that 85% of rail passengers travelling to London come from East Anglia and the South East.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17. In the last ten years 
[normal]there has been a far greater growth in rail passenger numbers in London and the South East than there has in long distance.
[normal]Rail [bold]passenger journeys (millions)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]London and SE operators[bold]Regional operators[bold]Long-distance operators[bold]2002-03
[normal]679
[normal]219.2
[normal]77.2
[normal]2012-13
[normal]1032.9
[normal]341.1
[normal]127.8
[normal]Increase during ten years
[normal]353.9
[normal]121.9
[normal]50.6
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]18. A growth of 353 million is seven times the growth of 
[normal]long distance passenger journeys.
[normal]http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/pass-rail-usage-2013-14-q1.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19. Euston had just 2,821 standing passengers and the majority of 
[normal]these were on London Overground and London Midland trains. Virgin Trains carry just 2% of national rail passengers. So why build an ultra high speed intercity line serving the North West when its trains are s
[normal]ome of the least overcrowded,
[normal] the vast majority 
[normal]of travellers to London don’t come from that direction
[normal] and the biggest growth of passenger numbers has been for commuters 
[normal]in the London area
[normal]?
[normal] The impro
[normal]ved Thameslink service 
[normal]in 2018 
[normal]will only
[normal] address a small proportion of these overcrowding issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Disrup[bold]tion effects[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]20. While being ready to criticise alternatives to HS2 due to the disruption that they will supposedly cause, the DfT has not indicated how much disruption will be caused by the construction of HS2 itself.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21. The building of HS2 will cause 
[normal]very 
[normal]severe disruption at Euston for approximately 9 years. It is likely that Euston station will be closed for some weekends and for some bank holiday periods. The number of platforms serving classic rail will be permanently reduced from 18 to 13 and the 
[normal]number of approach tracks from 6 to 4. This will almost certainly reduce the peak time capacity o
[normal]f Euston on a permanent basis (for classic trains).
[normal]http://www.railnews
[normal].co.uk/news/2013/04/19-hs2-set-to-abandon-complete.html
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22. There will be severe disruption in Camden. This will affect London Overground services which carry 25,000 passengers daily. It will also affect freight operations on the most important cross L
[normal]ondon freight route. It will also cause traffic chaos and se
[normal]riously impact Camden Market. HS2
[normal] will also have effects on the 
[normal]existing 
[normal]rail network where it joins other routes such as at north of St Pancras (HS1), Old Oak Common, north of Lichfield, Crewe, n
[normal]ear Wigan, Toton and Church Fenton. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]23. 
[normal]In addition HS2’s
[normal] construction will affect road users for an extended period with the need to cross the M1 (6
[normal] 
[normal]times), M42 (6 times), M56 (3 times), M6 (3 times) and M62 (2 times) as well as 47 crossings of trunk ro
[normal]ads.
[normal] To bring about its construction, many large trucks will be using any roads from motorways to narrow country lanes for several years.
[normal]http://www.cpre.org.uk/what-we-do/transport/rail/update/item/3391-striking-new-hs2-maps-launched
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]24. By contrast the 51M Optimised Alternative which does meet the DfT’s forecast passenger growth requirements 
[normal](through an increase of standard class capac
[normal]ity on each train) 
[normal]would need work at just three points on the WCML. Grade separated junctions 
[normal]would need to be built 
[normal]at Ledburn and Colwich, and laying of additional track to increase freight capacity between Rugby and 
[normal]Nuneaton. For the latter, weekend se
[normal]rvices could be diverted via other rail routes while the work is undertaken. 
[normal]The 51M Optimised Alternative requires no disruption at Euston, Camden or the other places which will be affected by the construction of HS2. 
[normal]Talk of 14 years of weekend working i
[normal]s nothing other than unfounded scaremongering. A journalist can see through that deception.
[normal]http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/r
[normal]oad-and-rail-transport/10423076/Lies-at-the-heart-of-case-for-HS2.html
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Omissions[bold]&#xa0;[bold]25. 
[normal]It has been estimated that HS2 will provide an extra 10,000 passengers per hour into the Underground network at Euston in addition to the existing 7000 per hour at peak periods. Source: Section 3.6, (page 20) HS2 Ltd Route Engineering Report.  
[normal](This appea
[normal]rs to be no longer available on the internet, although I still have a copy)
[normal]26. 
[normal]As is well known, the Underground is another British railway system that is very short of capacity at peak times. To more than double the demand at Euston without providing add
[normal]itional Underground capacity is unworkable. As Transport for London has pointed out, it will require the building of Crossrail 2.
[normal] This has not been included in the HS2 budget.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Regional Regeneration[bold]&#xa0;[bold]27. Several independent people 
[normal]or organisations 
[normal]have stu
[normal]died the 
[normal]regional 
[normal]effects of high speed rail in other countries. Professor Tomaney provided comprehensive oral and written evidence to this committee in 2011 on the subject of high speed rail. His views were that the amount of regional regeneration being c
[normal]reated would be small, and if it did exist then the regional beneficiary would be the capital
[normal],
[normal] in this case London. Other independent studies of actual evidence have reached similar conclusions.
[normal]http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/1185/11071201.htm
[normal]http://www.publications.parliament
[normal].uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/writev/rail/m14.htm
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Debt and Subsidy[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]28. 
[normal]The UK has a national debt of approximately £1.2 trillion. Network Rail ha
[normal]s a debt of £30 billion which some expect
[normal] to rise to £50 billion by 2020.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29. 
[normal]The debt that China has incurring in building its high speed lines reached US $ 640 billion by the end of 2012.  
[normal]http://www.nytimes
[normal].com/2012/12/27/business/global/worlds-longest-high-speed-rail-line-opens-in-china.html?_r=0
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]30. 
[normal]Zhao Jian, a professor at Beijing Jiaotong University, said he worries that the cost of the project might have created a hidden debt bomb that threatens Ch
[normal]ina’s banking system.
[normal] 
[normal]“In China, we will have a debt crisis — a high-speed rail debt 
[normal]crisis,” he told the Washington Post. “I think it is more serious than your subprime mortgage crisis. 
[normal]http://factsanddetails.com/china/cat13/sub86/item1848.html
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]   
[normal]31. 
[normal]Japan was the pioneer of high speed rail in the 1960s but within two decades had accumulated massive debts. The system was privatised and the $280 billion debt was transferred to 
[normal]the taxpayer and is still being paid off. Apparently four of the seven operators are still government owned, and it is thought that the privately owned operators receive concessionary usage fees. In addition, the three private operators receive another $2 
[normal]billion annually from the government. These subsidises are needed despite Japan having the highest rate of rail use in the developed world.
[normal]http://www.cc-hsr.org/assets/pdf/bnote-10.pdf
[normal]http://www.policymic.com/articles/1512/high-speed-rail-hardly-an-investment-in-future
[normal]http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/2010/03/america-s-coming-high-speed-rail-financial-disaster
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]32. 
[normal]The French accounting system treats taxpayer subsidies as “commercial revenues”. So the French programme’s $1
[normal].75 billion “profit” occurs through a $10 billion annual subsidy according to a study by Amtrak in 2008. The national rail infrastructure assets were transferred to 
[normal]Réseau Ferré de France (RFF) in 1997. Between RFF and SNCF there was an accumulated debt of
[normal] €38 billion from building lines for the TGV by 2011. To deal with this debt, RFF is expected to increase track fees by 40% between 2008 and 2012 to reduce this debt. SNCF has threatened to cancel low ridership routes and has indicated that its reduced pro
[normal]fitability will make it impossible to renew its 1981 fleet of TGVs before 2020. TGV fares are being increased by more than twice the rate of inflation and in some cases even more.
[normal]http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2011/09/24/after-30-years-tgv-service-prospers-even-as-its-future-is-questioned/
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33. 
[normal]It 
[normal]is understood that Spain spends nearly $3 billion on high speed rail subsidies annually and Germany more than $1 billion per year. We also know that t
[normal]he high speed line between Amsterdam, Rotterdam 
[normal]and Breda (in the Netherlands) was
[normal] saved from bankruptcy w
[normal]ith a 
[normal]£250m government bailout. It had
[normal] been losing £320,000 per day due to disastrous levels of patronage.
[normal]   
[normal]http://capoliticalnews.com/2012/04/15
[normal]/grimes-new-high-speed-rail-biz-plan-crashes-into-reality/
[normal]http://money.cnn.com/2009/06/10/news/economy/high_speed_rail/index.htm
[normal]http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/9000166/High-speed-rail-A-250m-lesson-for-Britains-rail-enthusiasts.html
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]34. 
[normal]This over-estimation of passenger demand leads to debts and subsidies being required from governments. 
[normal]In July 2010 a World Bank report cautioned that governments planning high-speed rail
[normal]systems:  
[normal]“. . should also contemplate the near-certainty of cop
[normal]ious and continuing budget
[normal]support for the debt”.
[normal] 
[normal]See summary page 1.
[normal]http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/2010/07/26/000334955_20100726032714/Rendered/PDF/558560WP0Box341SR1v08121jul101final.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35. 
[normal]Some countries have seen the light; Poland has decided not to build a high speed rail ne
[normal]twork, Portugal has abandoned plans to build three high speed lines one of which would have linked to Spain.
[normal] In June 2013, France shelved all TGV projects not currently under construction for 17 years.
[normal]http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/polish-high-speed-rail-project-cancelled.html
[normal]http://www.the
[normal]portugalnews.com/news/high-speed-rail-u-turn/27691
[normal]http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/france-shunts-new-tgv-projects-into-a
[normal]-siding-8676909.html
