[normal]Adverse effect on classic rail[bold]&#xa0;[bold]36. 
[normal]The president of
[normal] the SNCF, Guillaume Pépy thought that France wa
[normal]s going too fast in its further construction of high speed lines. TGV fares have increased by 100% in the last decade compared to about 30% for car travel. Pépy went on to say: 
[normal]The whole basis of the high-speed rail revolution – that the TGV should be the 
[normal]"normal" means of travel, not just something affordable by the business elite – is under threat. 
[normal]The SNCF president also described the state railways as: 
[normal]Decaying... facing a financial impasse... and heading for the wall. 
[normal]He should know better than most.  
[normal]http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/life-on-the-fast-track-thirty-years-of-the-tgv-2265455.html
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]37. 
[normal]Millions of people u
[normal]sing commuter lines every day, particularly around Paris, have suffered years of overcrowding, dirty trains and unreliable lines. Pépy said there is an urgent need to increase capacity on these lines. Following a fatal rail accident outside Paris in July 2
[normal]013, the Transport Minister Fr
[normal]é
[normal]d
[normal]é
[normal]ric Cuvillier commented that regional lines had been underfunded for many years as investment went to high-speed lines.
[normal]http://www.ft.com/cms/
[normal]s/0/622bcdc2-779a-11e2-b95a-00144feabdc0.html
[normal]http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/europe/article3816469.ece
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]38. While significant spending 
[normal]for rail 
[normal]is planned 
[normal]in the UK 
[normal]for Control Period 5 (2014 – 19), there is nothing to say that such a level of spending is affordable on an ongoing basis alongside HS2. It should not be forgotten that our classic rail will continue to transport most of our rail passengers; such
[normal] lines need regular maintenance and many parts of the country seek further enhancements e.g. electrification from Bristol to the South West.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About the author[bold]39. I have been studying High Speed Two in fine detail for more than two years. I live at least 1
[normal]6 miles from the proposed route. I am a director of HS2 Action Alliance and a member of South Northants Action Group. This submission is my own and is not on behalf of any other organisation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]40. 
[normal]I believe HS2 will not address the most pressing issue of o
[normal]vercrowded commuter trains to the south and east of London. If the Government is determined to increase the capacity for users of the West Coast Main Line, then it should adopt the 51M Optimised Alternative which is far cheaper
[normal], can be introduced much soon
[normal]er and with less disruption than HS2. There is no logical basis for spending £50 (+) billion to supplement the capacity of a line which carries 
[normal]just 
[normal]2% of our rail passengers and does not have the standing passenger issues which ma
[normal]ny other lines have. How 
[normal]will HS2
[normal] be helping the other 98% of rail travellers? HS2 is a totally ill conceived project and many people have not even studied the finer details.
[normal] If they did, they would understand its many 
[normal]fundamental 
[normal]shortcomings.
